name: Functional humerus length
description: Distance from the proximal point of the articular head to the distal mid-point of the trochlea.

name: Deltoid length of the humerus
description: Distance from the proximal point of the articular head to the distal end of the deltoid tuberosity.

name: Transverse diameter of the humerus
description: Transverse width of the humerus at the diaphyseal midpoint.

name: Anteroposterior diameter of the humerus
description: Anteroposterior depth of the humerus taken at a distance of 35% of the humeral length from the distal articular surface (Bicknevicius et al 1993).

name: Diameter of the epicondyles
description: Transverse width of the humerus across the epicondyles.

name: Total ulna length
description: Distance from the tip of the olecranon process to the distal articular surface of the ulna.

name: Olecranon length
description: Distance along the long axis of the ulna from the tip of the olecranon process to the centre of the trochlear notch.

name: Functional ulna length
description: Difference between total ulna length UL and olecranon length OL.

name: Transverse diameter of the ulna
description: Transverse width of the ulna at the diaphyseal midpoint.

name: Functional femur length
description: Distance from the proximal point of the femoral head to the distal point of the femoral condyles.

name: Distal extension of greater trochanter
description: Distance from the proximal point of the femoral head to the distal end of the greater trochanter.

name: Transverse diameter of the femur
description: Transverse width of the femur at the diaphyseal midpoint.

name: Tibia length
description: Distance between the proximal and distal articular surfaces of the tibia.

name: Proximal tibia length
description: Distance from the proximal articular surface of the tibia to the distal point of the tibial tuberosity.

name: Transverse diameter of the tibia
description: Width of the tibia at the diaphyseal midpoint.

name: Shoulder moment index
description: Deltoid length of the humerus divided by the functional length of the humerus (DLH/HL × 100). This index is an indication of the mechanical advantage of the deltoid and major pectoral muscles acting across the shoulder joint.

name: Humerus robustness index
description: Transverse diameter of the humerus divided by functional length of the humerus (TDH/HL × 100). It gives an indication of the robustness of the humerus.

name: Epicondyle index
description: Epicondylar width of the humerus divided by functional length of the humerus (DEH/HL × 100). It gives an indication of the relative width available for the origin of the flexor, pronator, and supinator muscles of the forearm. It is considered a good indicator of fossoriality (Hildebrand, 1985; Lessa & Stein, 1992).

name: Index of fossorial ability
description: Length of the olecranon process divided by the functional ulna length (OL/FUL × 100). This index gives a measure of the mechanical advantage of the triceps and dorso-epitrochlearis muscles in elbow extension. It is also considered a good indicator of fossoriality.

name: Ulna robustness index
description: Transverse diameter of the ulna divided by the functional ulna length (TDU/FUL × 100). It gives an indication of the robustness of the forearm and the relative width available for the insertion of muscles involved with pronation and supination of the forearm and flexion of the manus and digits.

name: Gluteal index
description: Distal extension of greater trochanter divided by the functional femoral length (DMT/FL × 100). It gives a measure of the mechanical advantage of the gluteus medius muscle and the velocity of femur extension.

name: Femur robustness index
description: Transverse diameter of the femur divided by the functional femoral length (TDF/FL × 100). It gives an idea of capacity to support body mass and to withstand vertical forces associated with velocity increase (Biewener & Taylor 1986; Demes et al., 1994).

name: Tibial spine index
description: Proximal tibia length divided by the length of the tibia (PT/TL × 100). It gives an indication of strength of the leg and the relative width available for the insertion site of the gracilis, semitendinosus and semimembranosus muscles and the foot flexors. It is important in the flexion of the leg during the first phase of the gait. Proximal insertion is related to greater speed during the initial propulsor movement (Elftman, 1929).

name: Tibia robustness index
description: Transverse diameter of the tibia divided by the tibial length (TDT/TL × 100). It gives an indication of the strength of the leg and the relative width available for the origins of the muscles acting across the ankle.

name: Orientation of the m. masseter posterior
description: on the lateral plane, it was estimated as the angle between the distance ‘middle point of the dorsal border of the jugal fossa – post-condyloid process’ and the occlusal plane.

name: Orientation of the jugal fossa
description: on the lateral plane, it was estimated as the angle between the dorsal border of the fossa and the occlusal plane. The increase of this angle represents a more suitable orientation of the fossa for the origin of the m. masseter posterior.

name: Length of the masseteric rostral fossa
description: between the anterior border of the fossa and the anterior border of DP4. It is an estimation of the disposition of the m. masseter medialis pars infraorbitalis. A long fossa indicates a more oblique orientation of the muscle and hence a greater involvement in generating propalinal movement of mandible.

name: Orientation of the m. masseter lateralis
description: on the transverse craneomandibular cross section of each articulated skull and mandible, it was estimated as an angle assessed trigonometrically on the basis of zygomatic breadth, jaw width and the distance ‘zygomatic arch – masseteric crest’. This angle was calculated as ML = tan arc ZMC/[(JW – ZB)/2]. It was assumed to estimate the degree of in- volvement of the muscle in the medial displacement of the mandible (see Fig. 1 in Greaves, 1980). An angle ≥ 90 ◦ implies no lateromedial force component for the m. masseter lateralis.

name: Orientation of the m. pterygoideus internus
description: on the horizontal plane, it was assessed as the angle between the line of action, ‘origin (pterygoid fossa) – insertion (pterygoid shelf)’, of the muscle, and the craneomandibu- lar sagittal axis. It was assumed that the more lateromedially oriented the muscle, the more medial movement of the mandible during mastication (Woods & Howland, 1979; Woods & Mckeen, 1989; Vassallo & Verzi, 2001).

name: Orientation of the pterygoid fossa
description: on the horizontal plane, it was measured as the angle between the lateral border of the fossa and the craneomandibular sagittal axis. It represents an additional estimation of the line of action of the m. pterygoideus internus.

name: Orientation of the m. pterygoideus externus
description: on the horizontal plane, it was assessed as the angle between the line of action, ‘origin (pterygoid plate) – insertion (medial surface of the condyle)’, of the muscle, and the craneomandibular sagittal axis. It was assumed that the more lateromedially oriented the muscle, the more medial movement of the mandible during mastication (Woods & Howland, 1979; Woods & Mckeen, 1989).

name: Orientation of medial border of the glenoid fossa
description: on the horizontal plane, measured as the angle of this border with respect to the sagittal axis of the skull. It was assumed that the disposition of the medial border of the fossa influences the main movement of the condyle in the fossa during mastication.

name: Orientation of the enamel band
description: measured surrounding the anterior lobe of the molars

name: Predominant orientation of the whole enamel band
description: obtained as an average between the prevailing orientation of the enamel band in the anterior and the posterior lobes of the molars.

name: Shoulder moment index
interpretation: indication of the mechanical advantage of the deltoid and major pectoral muscles acting across the shoulder joint

name: Humeral robustness index
interpretation: indicator of general resistance of the bone

name: Index of fossorial ability
interpretation: measure of the mechanical advantage of the triceps and dorsoepitrochlearis muscles in elbow extension, also a good indicator of fossoriality

name: Femur robustness index
interpretation: capacity for supporting body mass and to withstand the vertical forces associated with speed increase
